{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"932eb912-75f3-4455-9e0d-dfc646bdd4e5","content":"I'll set up the GitHub Actions workflow for NuGet trusted publishing via OIDC. Let me create the necessary files.","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_V8n1X1DUFbqs0f52Hgw5kc","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p .github/workflows","description":"Create workflows directory","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflows directory"}],"interactionId":"e5e93556-3b8f-47ae-9a93-5fa72b6764f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project and workflows don't exist yet. I'll need to create the directory structure and the GitHub Actions workflow for NuGet trusted publishing. Let me set this up properly.\n\nFor NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC), you need:\n1. A GitHub Actions workflow that uses OIDC to authenticate with nuget.org\n2. Configuration on nuget.org to trust the GitHub Actions workflow\n\nLet me create:\n1. The workflow file for publishing\n2. Explain how to configure nuget.org\n\nThe workflow needs:\n- `permissions: id-token: write` for OIDC\n- Use `dotnet nuget push` with `--source` pointing to nuget.org\n\n\n- Request an OIDC token from GitHub and exchange it for NuGet credentials\n\nOn nuget.org, I'll need to configure a trusted publisher that specifies the GitHub repository, workflow, and optionally the environment to establish the trust relationship. In GitHub Actions, I need to request an OIDC token with the `id-token: write` permission, then exchange it at nuget.org's token endpoint to get a short-lived API key for pushing the package. Actually, I think the most accurate current approach uses `dotnet nuget push` with the NuGet.org source URL, but instead of an API key, you pass the GitHub OIDC token directly. Let me think through how this actually works based on NuGet's documentation and how other registries handle OIDC — the workflow would need to exchange the OIDC token and then use it for authentication during the push step.\n\nWriting the workflow configuration...\n\nBut I'm realizing that `dotnet nuget push` might not directly support OIDC authentication yet, so there's probably an intermediate step needed to convert the OIDC token into something NuGet can use. Getting the OIDC token directly as the API key is the approach—I can retrieve it through GitHub Actions using either the `github-script` action or environment variables, then pass it straight to `dotnet nuget push` for NuGet.org to validate against the trusted publisher configuration.\n\nI'm going to settle on the pattern I'm most confident in: setting up `id-token: write` permissions, using a `nuget` GitHub environment, obtaining the OIDC token with the correct audience, and using it as the API key for the push command.","outputTokens":2020,"requestId":"1401:DC2FD:1CF57A5:200BD97:69FA90D6"},"id":"aac26664-018a-4f89-b62e-639005aec1aa","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:53:12.760Z","parentId":"adfc4adc-5be6-402a-808b-b6cdba338cc6"}
